# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: efootball-open
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:efootball-open/2007-in-esports] In Major League Gaming, Team Final Boss beat Team Carbon to win the MLG Las Vegas 2007 National Championship.
[src:efootball-open/2007-in-esports] In the Championship Gaming Series their series began in 2007, with the 2007 Championship Gaming Series season.
[src:efootball-open/2007-in-esports] At the time it was the most expensive esports tournament of all time.
[src:efootball-open/2013-in-esports] This article documents the year 2013 in esports.
[src:efootball-open/2014-in-esports] List of events in 2014 in esports (also known as professional gaming).
[src:efootball-open/2016-in-esports] List of events in 2016 in eSports (also known as professional gaming).
[src:efootball-open/2017-in-esports] List of events in 2017 in eSports (also known as professional gaming).
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The **2017 Visa Vegas eRace** was an eSports Formula E race held on January 7, 2017, at The Venetian Resort Hotel Casino in Las Vegas, Nevada, as part of the Sports Business Innovation Summit at the 2017 Consumer Electronics Show.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] This race, unlike others, did not count towards the 2016-17 season and was not held on a real track.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Ten sim racers—competitors who typically enter simulation racing video games—raced against regular series drivers on a simulated course for a $1 million total prize fund, a record in eSports racing history.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The race consisted of two races: a 14-lap qualifying race for the slowest 20 qualifiers to determine positions 11 to 20 for the 20-lap main race; and a 20-lap main race.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] An earlier qualifying session, divided into five groups of six cars, determined the first ten starting positions.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Bono Huis, a Dragon sim driver, led every session and won the event from pole position.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] António Félix da Costa, a professional driver, won the earlier qualifying race.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Huis led for the majority of the race until the mandatory virtual pit stops to change into a second car, when Mahindra's Olli Pahkala took over.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala finished first on the road after leading the final five laps, but he was penalised 12 seconds after it was discovered that a software bug allowed him to use FanBoost for longer than allowed.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Felix Rosenqvist, the highest-placed professional driver for Mahindra, took second, while Pakhala's penalty dropped him to third.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The eRace received mixed reviews in the media.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Those who criticised the race criticised its organisation because multiple technical issues caused a half-hour delay in the main event, and one driver was forced to withdraw from both races due to simulator issues.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Positive reviewers expressed their belief that the event's consequences could lead to a professional eSports racing series and aid in the resolution of accessibility issues, as well as for others to use it as an alternative career to traditional motor racing.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Following the eRace, some sim racers were adopted into the teams to which they were assigned, assisting their real-life development through car testing and advice.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Luis Pachon, the founder of the Madrid-based start-up company Cloud Sport, proposed the idea for an eRace in Las Vegas to Formula E (FE) CEO Alejandro Agag, who quickly understood Pachon's intention and began work soon after.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] *iRacing* was reportedly an early contender for an association with FE, but the costs of laser scanning the track, and the lack of a wider benefit of putting in the effort of constructing the circuit, meant it was not cost effective.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Agag revealed the eRace plans to *Reuters* in June 2016, and announced that it would take place during the 2017 Consumer Electronics Show (CES).
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] FE had previously held eRaces at all championship rounds, in which spectators competed against professional racing drivers in the eVillage of the hosting race track.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The eRace was officially confirmed at the 2016 London ePrix the following month.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] It was held on January 7, 2017, as part of CES' Sport Business Innovation Summit at The Venetian Resort Hotel Casino, but it did not count towards the 2016–17 championship and no points were awarded.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] For this event, FE partnered with ELEAGUE and featured commentary from Jack Nicholls and Dario Franchitti.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The eRace featured 20 FE competitors from the regular season grid and ten sim racing drivers who qualified for the event by competing in the Road to Vegas Challenge, a four-race elimination contest held between October 16 and December 4, 2016.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Former Formula Ford 1600 driver Graham Carroll and iRacing world champion Greger Huttu qualified first and second for the eRace.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Each of the ten sim drivers was assigned to one of the ten genuine FE teams at random.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] For realism, each participant wore a flame-proof race suit and drove identical virtual cars, with the only difference being team liveries and personal numbers for identification.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Pit stops to virtually switch to a second car were mandatory.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The race was regulated by FE's sporting director, and motorsport's world governing body, the Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The total prize fund was $1 million (the largest in eSports racing history), and was broadcast on the live streaming platform Twitch.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Cloud Sport designed the 3.14-mile (5.05 km) long anti-clockwise track, which was publicly unveiled on January 6.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Drivers started on South Las Vegas Boulevard, passing hotels and casino resorts such as the Luxor and the MGM Grand.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Cloud Sport supplied and regulated the Playseat simulation equipment which operated on the racing video game *rFactor 2.* Thrustmaster TS-PC steering wheels and T3PA pedals were fitted to the equipment.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The stewards sealed and approved all computers to ensure parity.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] External ports were blocked to prevent anyone from connecting personal components.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Drivers were unable to feel G-forces during the race, so Cloud Sport programmed the vehicles to respond to the inertia created by sudden acceleration.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] This created a realistic driving experience, as vehicles tilted onto three wheels during sharp cornering, and the cars' performance deteriorated when they were damaged.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The Vegas eRace was heavily promoted beforehand.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] If all you do is race on simulators at home, then maybe they are pretty good!." According to Mahindra's Felix Rosenqvist, the sim racers would have an advantage due to their experience, but it would not be as significant after learning the circuit.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Four practice sessions were held before the qualification race on January 7.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The first session, held on January 6, lasted half an hour and was attended by sim drivers, followed by an identically timed session for professional racing drivers fifteen minutes later.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] On the morning of January 7, the final two sessions for sim and professional drivers each lasted fifteen minutes.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Bono Huis set the fastest time for Dragon in the combined opening practice session, 1 minute, 28.456 seconds, half a second faster than anyone else.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] His closest rival was professional driver Rosenqvist, who finished second, ahead of third-placed Graham Carroll and Virgin's José María López in fourth.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Piquet was fifth, ahead of sixth-placed António Félix da Costa.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Sam Bird, Enzo Bonito, Olli Pahkala and Frijns rounded out the top ten fastest drivers in the session.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Huis again led the combined time sheets in the second practice session, this time with a lap of 1 minute, 28.142 seconds, more than half a second faster than second-placed Frijns; Rosenqvist was third, Félix da Costa was fourth, Petar Brljak was fifth, and Graham Carroll was sixth.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala was seventh, Bonito eighth, David Greco ninth and López tenth.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Saturday afternoon's 50 minute qualifying session was divided into five groups of six cars.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The groups were determined by a lottery system and were permitted six minutes of on-track activity.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The fastest five overall competitors in all five groups participated in a "Super Pole" session with one driver on the track at any time going out in reverse order from fifth to first.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Each of the five drivers was limited to one timed lap and the starting order was determined by their' fastest times.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] (Super Pole from first to fifth, and group qualifying from sixth to tenth).
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Huis continued to top every session throughout the eRace meeting and achieved pole position with a lap of 1 minute, 28.631 seconds.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] He received a $25,000 automatic award for his achievement.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Rosenqvist, whose fastest lap was two-tenths of a second slower, joined Huis on the front row.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Sim racers rounded out the top ten, with Aleksi Uusi-Jaakkola third and Graham Carroll fourth.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Greco finished fifth out of five super pole competitors.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Sixth to tenth place went to Pahkala, Patrik Holzmann, Huttu, Bonito, and Alkesi Elomaa.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Lucas di Grassi, Ma Qinghua, Bird, Maro Engel, Jean-Éric Vergne, Jérôme d'Ambrosio, Daniel Abt, Sébastien Buemi, Mitch Evans, Stéphane Sarrazin, Loïc Duval, Nico Prost, Oliver Turvey, Adam Carroll, Petar Brjlak (who crashed during his run) and Nick Heidfeld completed the starting order.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] From 15:25 Pacific Standard Time (PST) (UTC+08:00), the slowest 20 drivers from group qualifying competed in a 14-lap qualifying race to determine positions 11 to 20 on the grid.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] D'Ambrosio failed to start due to technical problems with his racing pod.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] In a race marred by multiple crashes that resulted in several cars losing bodywork parts, López led from the start until Félix da Costa closed in on him and overtook him on the outside at turn five.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Félix da Costa led the rest of the race to finish first and start 11th in the main race.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] López finished second and Frijns came third.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Outside the top three, Piquet secured fourth and was followed closely behind by Evans and Bird in fifth and sixth.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Defending series champion Buemi took seventh ahead of di Grassi in eighth.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The final two qualifiers were Di Grassi's teammate Abt and Duval in ninth and tenth.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The "Fan Boost" feature, which provided an additional 100 kW (130 hp) of power for six seconds in the driver's second car, was a unique feature of FE.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] A fan vote determined which three drivers were allowed to use the boost.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Pakhala, López, and Greco were given the extra power for the Vegas eRace.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The race was due to begin at 16:05 PST, but due to multiple technical issues, it was delayed for half an hour and reduced from 28 to 20 laps.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Di Grassi failed to start due to a simulator control issue.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The exact number of viewers was not disclosed.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Huis maintained the lead from the standing start entering the first corner and began to expand a small lead over Rosenqvist in the opening laps, who could not maintain the leader's pace.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Towards the end of lap one, Holzmann clipped the outside wall out of the final corner, speared across the start/finish straight, and collected Félix da Costa, ending both drivers' chances of a podium finish.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Holzmann retired, but Félix da Costa continued despite minor car damage.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Piquet dropped to 17th on the first lap, but returned to 14th by lap seven.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] By the third lap, Bird had moved up to sixth.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The mandatory virtual pit stops required all drivers to change cars, began at the end of lap seven, when Bird entered the pit lane.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala left a multi-car battle for third with Uusi-Jaakkola, Greco, and Graham Carroll at the conclusion of the next lap in order to make his mandatory pit stop.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala left with a clear track ahead of him, and because no other driver was impeding him, he set a series of fast lap times.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] On the tenth lap, Graham Carroll got a run on Uusi-Jaakkola leaving the final corner and steered onto the inside line into the first turn chicane.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Greco made it three abreast on the outside.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] He and Uusi-Jaakkola collided, and the latter touched Graham Carroll's left-rear wheel.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Two of the cars barrel-rolled through the trackside catch fencing and into some palm trees.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The cars glitched quickly and re-rendered themselves onto the circuit.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Both Uusi-Jaakkola and Greco had lost a wheel and dropped several positions.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Virtual racing technology meant the trio emerged unhurt from the crash and the safety car was not used.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] As the eRace progressed, race leader Huis made an error, allowing Rosenqvist to close to within less than two seconds of him.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Huis and Rosenqvist made their pit stops together at the end of lap fifteen and emerged in second and third places.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Pakhala lapped in the 1 minute, 24 second range, moving him to the front of the field, and requiring Huis and Rosenqvist to focus on battling for second position.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Buemi dropped outside the top ten with four laps remaining when Piquet passed him for tenth.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Ussi-Jaakkola and Bonito battled for fourth, which ended in the latter's favour in the last three laps.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Pahkala was unchallenged for the rest of the eRace, and was first to cross the start/finish line.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Huis held off Rosenqvist in the closing laps for second.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Huis and Dragon filed a complaint with the race officials following the podium ceremony.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] An examination of data shared by viewers on Twitter shortly after the race revealed that Pahkala had used FanBoost illegally for approximately five laps, rather than the maximum of five seconds due to a software bug.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Hence, Pahkala had 12 seconds added to his race time and was demoted to third.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Huis inherited the victory with Rosenqvist second.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Bonito finished fourth, ahead of the Finnish duo of Uusi-Jaakkola and Huttu.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] The final classified finishers were López, Bird, Abt, Piquet, Buemi, Elomaa, Frijns, Duval, Greco, Félix da Costa, and Graham Carroll.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Huis received $200,000 for race victory and Greco got $10,000 for setting the fastest lap.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Huis commented on the victory: "It's very exciting to be here, racing in conjunction with pro drivers during one of the most renowned tech forward events.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Media reaction to the Vegas eRace was mostly positive.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] New England Sports Network's Pat McAssey noted that FE's partnership with ELEAGUE brought sim racing to a mainstream audience and argued that eSports can potentially solve accessibility issues because some people lack the money to purchase a go-kart.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] He argued that FE could help eRacing grow and allow others to use it as an alternative career path to traditional motor racing.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Curtis Moldrich, writing for *Alphr*, echoed similar sentiments, believing that the positive outcome of the Vegas eRace was a testament to FE's forward-thinking philosophy.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Other media outlets received the race more negatively.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] It lacked any sense of real weight or drama, and tied in with the glitches affecting some of the drivers it didn't come anywhere near to producing the excitement of real racing." Jonathan M.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Gitlin of *Ars Technica* felt short-changed watching the eRace and noted the large number of complaints about the quality of the graphics in the Twitch stream.
[src:efootball-open/2017-vegas-erace] Following the event, some of the competing sim racers were adopted into their respective teams and assisted in the real-life development of their cars through testing and advising, indicating that their opinions were taken seriously, according to FE's eSports manager Matt Huxley.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] eFootball World Championships (formerly known as the PES League and the eFootball League) is the official global eFootball championship organized by Konami, the publisher of the series.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] Established in France in the early 2000s, the competition later expanded internationally and has been directly managed by Konami since 2010.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] Historically, it served as the official 1v1 esports world championship for the Pro Evolution Soccer (PES) franchise.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] In 2020, the competition structure was reorganized as part of the newly established **eFootball Esports League**.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] Since **2023**, eFootball.Pro has been discontinued.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The **2023 eFootball.Open World Finals** became the first unified global finals since 2019, open to both amateur and professional players.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The event was held for the first time in **Tokyo, Japan**, at Konami’s renovated headquarters and its dedicated esports arena.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The most recent PES **3v3 World Champions** are the Brazilian team **eLiga Sul Stars**, who won the 3v3 PES League Finals on 29 June 2019, claiming a top prize of **US$75,000** divided among the players.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] This table shows the most decorated players from the 1v1 Championship.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] Those who have won the Championship and placed top three in another are included.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] Players who have recently done great results in the eFootball.Open competitions are more likely to be contracted by a professional club to represent them.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The first edition of this ambitious esports project, is played with Pro Evolution Soccer 2019, and will feature the esports section of 6 participating clubs such as FC Barcelona, Schalke 04, AS Monaco, Celtic FC, FC Nantes, Boavista, in a Coop 2vs2 format, with a regular league + playoff structure.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] On a championship day, two matches are played in each of the confrontations.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] Points are awarded for each match (3 points for a win, 1 point for a draw, 0 points for a loss).
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] A club can therefore earn up to six points on a single matchday.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] For the second edition, the number of teams was increased to 10 with the entry of Arsenal FC, Juventus FC, Manchester United FC or FC Bayern Munich, gaining media and public attention in more countries.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] There was also a huge increase in the prize pool which was divided into regular league final position, playoffs, as well as individual matchday prizes of €10,000 for MVP and Best Goal.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] In addition, at the end of the season, juicy monetary prizes were included for the MVP of the season, top scorer, top assist and best defender.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] This big step meant the entry into esports of several of the most important clubs in Europe who wanted to crown their triumph in efootball.pro 2020.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The 10 participating teams played in a regular league format, where the top 6 would advance to playoff play at the end of the season in a decisive weekend.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] Everything changed in the middle of the season, when the arrival of the covid pandemic caused the pause and then the definitive cancellation of efootball.pro 2020 in its on-site format in Barcelona.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The ***eFootball.Pro Cup*** is being organised exceptionally in 2020 to bridge the end of the season, following the discontinuation of the eFootball.Pro League.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] A total of €250,000 is awarded, plus the individual prizes of Best Goal of the Matchday, MVP of the day, during group stage and Playoffs.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The 10 teams are divided into two groups of five, from which the top two qualify for a knockout final phase, in a 3vs3 format.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The group stage is played in a single-elimination format.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The semi-finals are played over two legs, while the final is played over a single match.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] Final phase (semi-finals and final): 31 July.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The ***eFootball.pro 2020 - 2021*** was again organised in an online format, this time the whole season would take place in this way, with a 3vs3 regular league + playoffs format where the top 6 would advance to the finals.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] For this edition AS Roma and Gatalasaray were added as new participating teams, providing new opportunities for players to enter the professional scene.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The ***eFootball.pro 2022*** had a delay of several months, due to the uncertainty of whether to go back to the on-site format or stay online, in the end it went ahead with a short online format of a few months with finally 8 teams, after the absence of Juventus FC and Schalke 04.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The 8 participating teams were divided into 2 groups of 4, with the top 2 teams advancing to the final stage.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] For this edition, the format was changed to a 1vs1 competition, where clubs would still have to recruit at least 3 players.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] Each match would be played in 3 matches, where the strategy of what order to select your players in was of great importance.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The finals would be played in Bo3 format (ET and PK) where the team that won 2 matches would advance to the next round.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The ***eFootball.pro 2023***, the latest edition of the biggest competition in the history of competitive PES/eFootball scene was held again offline, in a 6-month format, almost returning to pre-Covid pandemic levels.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] It would be made up of a total of 8 participating teams, with the entry of AC Milan and FC Inter.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] All teams would have to hire 3 professional players for the season, with the option of substitutes.
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] The 2023 edition, as we said, would have an offline format in the Barcelona TV studio, with a 1vs1 regular league format (3 games against each rival) + Playoffs (bo3).
[src:efootball-open/efootball-open] In addition to the large pool of financial prizes, the best goal of the day and final phase, MVP of the Regular Phase and the Final Phase, would be added.
